It will be great if there is a feature on the 'Manage filter' page, which allow user to bulk delete saved filters. Some user might have more than 100 or 1,000 saved filters, it takes too long to delete them one by one when it's not useful anymore.

h3. Problem Definition
Presently, it is up to the user to decide if attachments should be copied when cloning an issue. In secure environments, administrators should have the ability to restrict the ability to copy attachments outside of the original issue.

h3. Suggested Solution
Either implement a flag to disable the copying of attachments globally, or implement it as a per-project feature.

h3. Why this is important
Cloning of attachments may lead to the leak of sensitive data (depending on who the clone is shared with).
Additionally, when using an add-on such as [Smart Attachments|https://marketplace.atlassian.com/apps/1212507/smart-attachments?hosting=server&tab=overview] to categorize attachments (and place restrictions on them), such data is lost during a clone operation.

h3. Workaround
Add the following css script in your Jira Announcement Banner (by following the steps on   [Configuring an announcement banner KB|https://confluence.atlassian.com/adminjiraserver/configuring-an-announcement-banner-938846985.html]), *Clone Attachments* checkbox will disappear:
{code:xml}
<script type="text/javascript">
// if an XHR request completed
AJS.$( document ).ajaxComplete(function( event,request, settings ) {
  // if it was a click on the Clone button
  if(settings.url.indexOf('CloneIssueDetails') >= 0){
    // hide the attachments checkbox
      AJS.$('form#clone-issue.aui > div.form-body > fieldset > fieldset.group > div.checkbox').each(function(){
        if($( this ).html().indexOf("clone-issue-clone-attachments") >= 0){
          $( this ).hide();
        }
      });
  }
});
</script>
{code}

h3. Problem Definition

Currrently, in [Connecting Jira applications to MySQL|https://confluence.atlassian.com/adminjiraserver/connecting-jira-applications-to-mysql-938846854.html] documentation, we provide the MySQL permission configuration for "For MySQL 5.5, MySQL 5.6, and MySQL 5.7.0 to MySQL 5.7.5" first before "For MySQL 5.7.6 and above":

{quote}
For MySQL 5.5, MySQL 5.6, and MySQL 5.7.0 to MySQL 5.7.5: 

GRANT SELECT,INSERT,UPDATE,DELETE,CREATE,DROP,ALTER,INDEX on <JIRADB>.* TO '<USERNAME>'@'<JIRA_SERVER_HOSTNAME>' IDENTIFIED BY '<PASSWORD>';
flush privileges;
For MySQL 5.7.6 and above, you must also include the REFERENCES permission:

GRANT SELECT,INSERT,UPDATE,DELETE,CREATE,DROP,REFERENCES,ALTER,INDEX on <JIRADB>.* TO '<USERNAME>'@'<JIRA_SERVER_HOSTNAME>' IDENTIFIED BY '<PASSWORD>';
flush privileges;
{quote}

If a user configured the permission for 5.7.5 in MySQL 5.7.6, certain feature such as project creation will silently fail. 


h3. Suggested Solution

Update the [Connecting Jira applications to MySQL|https://confluence.atlassian.com/adminjiraserver/connecting-jira-applications-to-mysql-938846854.html] documentation so the permission configuration for "MySQL 5.7.6 and above" is listed above "MySQL 5.5, MySQL 5.6, and MySQL 5.7.0 to MySQL 5.7.5" permission configuration.

This way, if a customer configured the MySQL permission meant for 5.7.6 in MySQL 5.7.5 and lower, he/she will see an error from the UI and the user can apply the correct permission.


h3. Workaround 

Apply the correct permission based on the version of MySQL provided in [Connecting Jira applications to MySQL|https://confluence.atlassian.com/adminjiraserver/connecting-jira-applications-to-mysql-938846854.html]
